  "text": "Django implements comprehensive SQL injection prevention through multiple mechanisms:\n\n**1. RawSQL Expression Sanitization (django/db/models/expressions.py:1236)**\nThe RawSQL class allows developers to include raw SQL expressions with parameter placeholders. The class stores both the SQL string and parameters separately (line 1242: `self.sql, self.params = sql, params`). The as_sql() method (line 1248) ensures parameters are kept separate from the SQL code.\n\n**2. raw() QuerySet Method Parameter Binding (django/db/models/query.py:1461, 2210)**\nThe raw() method on QuerySet and the RawQuerySet class provide safe raw SQL query execution. RawQuerySet stores parameters separately and passes them through the parameter binding chain. The params are preserved through initialization (line 2232: `self.params = params`) and used only during query execution.\n\n**3. RawQuery Class Parameter Adaptation (django/db/models/sql/query.py:150)**\nThe RawQuery._execute_query() method (line 203) implements critical parameter sanitization:\n- Line 209: `adapter = connection.ops.adapt_unknown_value` - Gets database-specific parameter adapter\n- Lines 210-217: Adapts parameters based on their type (tuple, dict, or None)\n- Line 220: `self.cursor.execute(self.sql, params)` - Executes with parameterized query\n\n**4. cursor.execute() Parameterization Enforcement (django/db/backends/utils.py:17)**\nThe CursorWrapper class enforces parameterized queries:\n- execute() method (line 78): Takes sql and params separately\n- _execute_with_wrappers() (line 88): Routes execution through wrappers\n- _execute() (line 94): Ensures params are passed separately to cursor.execute()\n\n**5. Parameter Adaptation (django/db/backends/base/operations.py:550)**\nThe adapt_unknown_value() method sanitizes parameters based on type:\n- Line 558-567: Checks parameter type and applies appropriate adaptation\n- Handles datetime, date, time, and Decimal types safely\n- Ensures values are converted to database-compatible format\n\n**6. SQL Identifier Quoting (django/db/models/sql/compiler.py:550 and django/db/backends/base/operations.py:413)**\nBoth quote_name_unless_alias() and quote_name() protect identifiers:\n- quote_name_unless_alias() (line 550): Wraps connection.ops.quote_name() with alias handling\n- Validates against dollar signs in column aliases (lines 556-562) on PostgreSQL\n- Uses database-specific quoting (backticks for MySQL, quotes for PostgreSQL/SQLite/Oracle)\n\n**7. Backend-Specific Implementations:**\n- django/db/backends/sqlite3/operations.py:167 - Uses double quotes for identifiers\n- django/db/backends/postgresql/operations.py:189 - Uses double quotes\n- django/db/backends/mysql/operations.py:173 - Uses backticks\n- django/db/backends/oracle/operations.py:391 - Uses double quotes with case handling\n\n**8. Alias Validation (django/db/backends/base/features.py:422)**\nThe prohibits_dollar_signs_in_column_aliases feature flag allows backends to enforce stricter alias validation. PostgreSQL sets this to True (django/db/backends/postgresql/features.py:73) to prevent column alias injection attacks via dictionary expansion with dollar signs.\n\n**9. FilteredRelation SQL Injection Prevention (django/db/models/query_utils.py:504)**\nThe FilteredRelation class prevents SQL injection in ON clause conditions:\n- The condition parameter is validated as a Q() instance (line 512-513)\n- resolve_expression() (line 542) builds filters safely using query.build_filter()\n- as_sql() (line 553) compiles the condition through the compiler, ensuring parameter binding\n\nThe chain of SQL injection prevention flows from high-level APIs (raw(), RawSQL) through the query compilation layer (compiler.quote_name_unless_alias), parameter adaptation (adapt_unknown_value), to the final execution layer (CursorWrapper.execute) where parameterized queries are enforced at the database driver level."
